  "prompt": "If a truck is hauling 1000 pounds of parakeets that are all sitting on their perch does it get 1000 pounds lighter if they all fly at the same time?",
  "response": "No, the truck does not become lighter when the parakeets fly. When the parakeets are perched, their weight is supported by the perch and the truck. When they fly, they are still part of the system and are exerting a downward force on the truck through the air. According to Newton's third law, for every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction. \n\nWhile the parakeets are in the air, they are still contributing their weight to the truck through the lift they generate. The truck will weigh roughly the same, whether the birds are perched or flying, because the air they displace while flying does create a downward force that equals their weight. Therefore, the total weight of the truck and the parakeets remains constant at 1,000 pounds plus the weight of the truck itself.",
